title CD - SIE Emergence & Homeostasis on Definition–Description Alignment - v1

note as GenerativeModelNote
  **GSM: Generative (Definitional) Model**

  Unlike classical descriptive models (VSM, GST), GSM primitives are
  **active definitions** that generate system structure, governance, and
  viability. SIE realizes this generative nature by continuously
  comparing definitions against described reality (Description plane),
  detecting mismatch, and driving remediation or emergence.

  This diagram illustrates the closed-loop through which generative
  definitions flow: Definition → Description → (mismatch) → Remediation
  → State → Description (re-observation).
end note

' ============================================================
' COMPONENT VIEW
'
' Purpose: make explicit how homeostasis and emergence articulate across
' Definition ↔ Description interactions.
' ============================================================

package "Definition Plane" as DefPlane #E8F4E8 {
  package "Definition DB\n(primitive invariants + storage)" as SDM #E8F4E8 {
    [Compilation\n(SIE DSL → CEL)] as Compiler
    [Governor\n(owns Policies)\n(Emergence + Decision)] as Governor
    [Supervisor\n(owns Rules)\n(Adaptation)] as Supervisor
    [Coherence\n(coherence + feasibility)\n(owned by Governor)] as Coherence
    [Definition Population\n(Bootstrap + Sync)] as DefPop
  }
}

actor "Decision Owner" as DecisionOwner

package "Description Plane" as DescPlane #E8F0FA {
  [Sourcing\n(Connectors)] as Sourcing
  [Domain Signal Adapters\n(Jira/CMDB/Repos/IdP)] as Signals
  [State Object Store] as StateStore
  [Evaluation Runtime\n(realizes SensorMechanisms)\n(Comparator)] as Comparator
  [Mismatch Builder\n(realizes Controller receptors)\n(Signal Builder)] as Mismatch
}

package "Remediation Plane" as RemPlane #F4E8E8 {
  [Operator\n(realizes Rules)\n(Homeostasis / Rule Execution)] as RuleEngine
  [Actuators\n(Executors)] as Actuators
}

package "State Plane" as StatePlane #F4F4E8 {
  [External Systems] as Ext
}

[Event Bus] as Bus

' ============================================================
' INFORMATION FLOWS
' ============================================================

SDM --> Compiler : definitions
Compiler --> Comparator : evaluable forms

Ext --> Sourcing : events/state
Ext --> Signals : domain facts
Signals --> Sourcing : normalize to sources
Sourcing --> StateStore : state objects
StateStore --> Comparator : measured state

Comparator --> Mismatch : evaluation outputs
Mismatch --> Bus : MismatchDetectedEvent

Bus --> Supervisor : mismatch signal
Supervisor --> RuleEngine : remediation/adaptation intent
RuleEngine --> Actuators : control actions
Actuators --> Ext : change state

Supervisor --> Governor : request coherence check
Governor --> Coherence : operate coherence checking
Coherence --> Governor : coherence + feasibility results
Governor --> Supervisor : classification + resolution guidance

Supervisor --> Governor : escalate(definition change needed)
Governor --> DecisionOwner : requestDecision(proposal + evidence)
DecisionOwner --> Governor : approve/reject
Governor --> Coherence : verify proposal coherence
Coherence --> Governor : verification report
Governor --> SDM : create/deprecate primitives + publish policy changes
Governor --> Bus : PrimitiveChangedEvent

DefPop --> SDM : import/sync primitives
note right of DefPop
  **Definition Population (non-emergent)**

  Bootstraps an SIE instance with known primitives,
  and continuously synchronizes definitions from
  authoritative sources (e.g. code repos, CMDB).

  It can CREATE/DEPRECATE primitives with provenance,
  but does NOT represent emergence by itself.

  Emergence begins only when mismatch/coherence evidence
  indicates that *sourcing/imported definitions are insufficient*
  (variety deficit / missing concept / persistent drift).
end note

note right of DecisionOwner
  **Decision Owner (concrete meaning):**
  A set of *input providers* for governor decisions, e.g.:
  - Human approvals (ITIP UI / change advisory)
  - Meta-policies and guardrails (auto checks)
  - Risk/impact summaries and audit requirements
  - External governance systems (tickets/approvals)

  This is an interface/component boundary, not a systemic primitive.
end note

' ============================================================
' HOMEOSTASIS / EMERGENCE ARTICULATION (TEXT)
' ============================================================

note bottom of Supervisor
  **Homeostasis (in SIE, across Definition–Description)**

  Paraphrase of your proposal (please confirm exact wording):
  - Homeostasis is the continuous process that keeps the Description Plane
    aligned with the Definition Plane, by detecting mismatch and acting.

  Slightly more systemics-faithful phrasing (SIE-specific):
  - Homeostasis is a negative-feedback control regime that continuously reduces
    Definition–Description mismatch by selecting actions (remediation) and/or
    tuning constraints within the current definitional structure.

  Canonical systemics statement:
  - Homeostasis is the maintenance of essential variables within viable bounds
    through negative feedback: deviations generate error signals which drive
    compensatory actions that damp deviations and preserve system identity.

  **Articulation rule:**
  - If mismatch is reducible without changing Policies or structural primitives,
    then homeostasis applies remediation and/or **Adaptation**
    (rule changes within current policy bounds); emergence is not opened.
  - If mismatch reflects a *variety deficit* (insufficient capability to meet
    constraints) or requires changing Policies / primitives, homeostasis
    escalates to emergence.

  **Ownership (3-level hierarchy):**
  - Operator REALIZES Rules (executes remediation)
  - Supervisor OWNS Rules and orchestrates first-order control
  - Governor OWNS Policies and governs second-order definition change

  In other words:
  - Homeostasis is not "owned" by a single level; it is implemented by the
    vertical Governor→Supervisor→Operator feedback topology.
  - This diagram's homeostasis view is an orchestration view of that topology
    (often implemented primarily by Supervisor + Operator services).
end note

note right of Mismatch
  **Mismatch detection (activable information)**

  Detectable gaps between Definition expectations and Description reality:
  - Coverage gap: required state object/event not sourced
  - Schema drift: sourced object violates archetype schema
  - Value deviation: constraint violation / drift
  - Reference gap: definition points to missing primitive
  - Variety deficit: feasibility NOT_FEASIBLE with current mechanisms

  Translation to triggers:
  - Homeostasis trigger: value deviation, schema drift (often fixable)
  - Emergence trigger: variety deficit, persistent coverage/reference gaps

  **Runtime realization:**
  - The Mismatch Builder can live in the Description Plane for streaming
    efficiency, but it conceptually produces events bound to controller
    receptors (Supervisor/Governor).

  **Ownership note (design choice):**
  - If Mismatch lives in Description Plane: closer to data + cheaper streaming;
    but must be definition-aware to label gaps.
  - If Mismatch lives in Definition Plane: better semantic correctness
    (definition-aware comparator); but higher coupling to sourcing/runtime.
end note

